[[File:Ban Dainagon Ekotoba - police.jpg|thumbnail|Depiction of ''{{ill|Ban Dainagon Ekotoba|ja|伴大納言絵詞}}'' showing a ''kebiishi'']]
[[File:Honen shonin eden - Police.jpg|thumbnail|''Kebiishi'' guarding {{ill|Chion-in|ja|知恩院}}]]

'''Kebiishi''' (検非違使, also pronounced ''kenbiishi'') were {{ill|Ritsuryō|ja|律令制}} officials in Japan classified as {{ill|Extra-statutory office|ja|令外官}}. The term refers to agents investigating and correcting violations (''hii'') on behalf of the emperor. Abbreviated as ''hii,'' they were civil servants of the ''kebiishi'' office. The Chinese-style titles (''唐名'') for ''sa'' and ''jō'' Ranks were ''Tingwei'' (廷尉). They managed security and governance in {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都}} and were first established in the early {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代}}. By the late Heian period, similar offices were also set up in the provinces.

== Overview ==

The ''kebiishi'' first appear in historical records from {{ill|Kōnin|ja|弘仁}} 7 (816), indicating they were likely established around this time. Since the {{ill|militia|ja|軍団 (古代日本)}} were abolished under {{ill|Emperor Kanmu|ja|桓武天皇}}, the court had effectively abandoned military forces. Consequently, crime in Kyoto increased, leading to the creation of the ''kebiishi'' by utilizing personnel from the {{ill|Emonfu|ja|衛門府}} (Imperial Guard). ''Kebiishi'' were selected from the military officers (''bugan'') of the Emonfu to fulfill policing duties. They were appointed by {{ill|senji|ja|宣旨}} (imperial decree) and did not have a specific {{ill|Rank equivalence (Ritsuryō)|ja|官位相当|1=Kan'i sōtō system|2=ja|3=官位相当制}}. However, ''kebiishi'' who reached the fifth Rank or higher gained access to the imperial court and became {{ill|tonōnin|ja|殿上人}}, making the position a milestone for the advancement of {{ill|samurai|ja|武士}}.

In 864, ''kebiishi'' offices were set up in the eastern and western marketplaces in Kyoto, where public punishments were conducted as deterrents.

In {{ill|Kanpyō|ja|寛平|1=Kanpyō (era)|lt=Kanpyō|qq= (era)|1=Kanpyō (era)|lt=Kanpyō|qq= (era)}} 7 (895), two ''kebiishi'' offices were established within the left and right Emonfu. However, by {{ill|Tenryaku|ja|天暦}} 1 (947), they were consolidated into a single office for efficiency, housed in the left office only.

The ''kebiishi'' gradually expanded their authority by assuming responsibilities from other institutions like the {{ill|Gyōbushō|ja|刑部省|1=Ministry of Justice (pre-modern Japan)|lt=Ministry of Justice|qq= (pre-modern Japan)|1=Ministry of Justice (pre-modern Japan)|lt=Ministry of Justice}} (judiciary), {{ill|Danjō-dai|ja|弾正台}} (policing and oversight), and {{ill|Kyōshiki|ja|京職}} (administration and governance of Kyoto). Over time, they wielded significant power.

By the late Heian period, the ''kebiishi'' introduced their customary legal practices, called ''{{ill|Chōrei|ja|庁例}}'', which diverged from traditional {{ill|Ritsuryō law|ja|律令}}. During this time, much of the office's work shifted to the residences of the ''{{ill|Bettō (Japan)|ja|別当}}'' (chief officials).

During the late Heian period, they were overshadowed by {{ill|Hokumen no Bushi|ja|北面武士}}, a military organization of the {{ill|Insei|ja|院政}} era. Under the {{ill|Kamakura shogunate|ja|鎌倉幕府}}, the establishment of the {{ill|Rokuhara Tandai|ja|六波羅探題}} further weakened the ''kebiishi.'' By the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代}}, their authority was transferred to the {{ill|Samurai-dokoro|ja|侍所}} of the {{ill|Muromachi shogunate|ja|Ashikaga Shogunate}}.

Despite this decline, the ''kebiishi'' retained certain administrative and judicial functions. Their role in tracking and apprehending criminals was taken over by the Samurai-dokoro during the {{ill|Jōwa (Muromachi period)|ja|貞和}} era. Records suggest their judicial functions lasted until {{ill|Shitoku|ja|至徳}} 3 (1386). Historian {{ill|Shigeaki Mori|ja|森茂暁}} identifies the ''kebiishi'' office's dissolution during the late Shitoku era.<ref>Shigeaki Mori, ''Research on Public and Military Relations in the Nanboku-chō Period'' (1984), pp. 321–353.</ref>

== Internal Positions ==

; {{ill|Bettō (Japan)|ja|別当}}
: Equivalent to the chief officer (''kami'') in the {{ill|Ritsuryō Four-Rank System|ja|四等官|1=Shitōkan}}. The title was referred to as ''Dailijing'' (大理卿) in Chinese. The ''bettō'' supervised the ''kebiishi'' but was not a ''kebiishi'' themselves. Appointees were typically middle- to high-Ranking court nobles.
; {{ill|Sa (official)|ja|佐}}
: Equivalent to the second officer (''suke''). ''Sa'' positions were often held by officials from the {{ill|Emonfu|ja|衛門府}} and served as de facto managers of the ''kebiishi'' office.
; {{ill|Daiyū|ja|大尉}}
: Equivalent to a judge (''jō''), usually appointed from the {{ill|Sakaue clan|ja|坂上氏}} or {{ill|Nakahara clan|ja|中原氏}}.
; {{ill|Shōyū|ja|少尉}}
: Equivalent to a junior officer (''jō'') and frequently held by samurai from prominent clans such as the {{ill|Minamoto clan|ja|源氏}} or {{ill|Taira clan|ja|平氏}}.
; {{ill|Daishi|ja|大志}} and {{ill|Shōshi|ja|少志}}
: Equivalent to clerks (''sakan''), usually occupied by young bureaucrats from prominent families.
; {{ill|Kantokuchō|ja|看督長}}
: Managed prisons but later focused on apprehending criminals. Known for their distinct uniform featuring red ''kariginu'' and white staffs.
; {{ill|Anju|ja|案主}}
: Administrative officers in the ''kebiishi'' office, initially limited to one but later increased in number.

== Cultural References ==
* {{ill|Ryūnosuke Akutagawa}}'s stories "{{ill|Rashōmon (short story)|ja|羅生門}}" and "{{ill|In a Grove|ja|藪の中}}" portray ''kebiishi'' as police-like figures.
* The video game ''{{ill|Heian Kyō Alien|ja|平安京エイリアン}}'' features ''kebiishi'' as player characters.

